body:
@jtattermusch, ok so I was able to compile a Portable Class Library "targeting" .NetStandard 1.5 with references to Google protobuf 3.1.0 and gRPC pre. I also added generated protobuf models as well as gRPC service and stubs. 

I tried to run this on an Android Emulator, which did not work (as probably expected). App crashes directly and Visual Studio looses connection without concrete error.
Will dig further tomorrow.

~~tl;dr my best guess is xamarin targets .netstandard 1.4, whereas grpc targets .netstandard 1.5, therefor it does not work (ref [using-xamarin-forms-with-net-standard](https://oren.codes/2016/07/09/using-xamarin-forms-with-net-standard/), and [grpc pre 1.0.1](https://www.nuget.org/packages/Grpc.Core/1.0.1-pre1) )~~ see update below

I finally got time to try again. I needed to start with a fresh environment, as I ran into several unrelated issues.

I created a PCL targeting .NetStandard 1.5. The project.json looks like this
`{
  "supports": {},
  "dependencies": {
    "Google.Protobuf": "3.1.0",
    "Grpc": "1.0.1-pre1",
    "Grpc.Core": "1.0.1-pre1",
    "NETStandard.Library": "1.6.0"
  },
  "frameworks": {
    "netstandard1.5": { "imports": [ "portable-net45+wpa81+wp8+win8" ] }
  }
}`
I also referenced proto models and a service (basically the greeter service from the tutorial).
That stuff compiles.

However when referenced in an Xamarin Android project, it first complained about a missing package. Can't remember what that was, and unfortunatly cant reproduce. My best guess is that Xamarin is not compatible with .NetStandard 1.5 ([using-xamarin-forms-with-net-standard](https://oren.codes/2016/07/09/using-xamarin-forms-with-net-standard/)). Seems it only works with netstandard1.4.

I played around with that setup (referenced the dll instead the project and some other stuff can't remember) and now Im in the state as 6 days before, where I actually can compile the android project, deploy that to the emulator, and it immediatly crashes. But that also happens for clean projects.  I think because of the beforementioned stuff its pointless to add the error descriptions here.

// Update: actually the first link provided states that when targeting iOs and Android .NetStandard 1.6 should be compatible

Anyone who found a solution to get grpc workin on xamarin right now? 

@yashton how did you build the grpc_csharp_ext.so, in your fork its build on x86 which fails in a "has unexpected e_machine: 3" error on my device. 
Btw. you dont need to copy the .so file on your device manually, you can use path sniffing: e.g. "lib\armeabi\libgrpc_csharp_ext_mobile.so" and make copy alway and AndroidNativeLibrary and the .so-file will be found automatically.
